# {{ adapter_name }}

Nautilus adapter for the `{{ source_type }}` source type, scaffolded with
`nautilus adapters new`.

## Develop

```bash
pip install -e ".[test]"
pytest -v          # SDK compliance suite
```

Replace the in-memory sample rows in `src/{{ package_name }}/__init__.py`
with your real data source.

## Use with a Nautilus broker

### Option A — installed package (entry-point discovery)

```bash
pip install -e .
```

The broker discovers `{{ class_name }}` via the `nautilus.adapters`
entry-point group. Reference it from a source block:

```yaml
sources:
  - id: my-source
    type: {{ source_type }}
    description: "..."
    classification: unclassified
    data_types: [generic]
    connection: "<dsn-or-path>"
```

Confirm it loaded:

```bash
nautilus adapters list
```

### Option B — local path (no packaging)

Skip installation and point the broker at the module file directly:

```yaml
adapters:
  - module_path: ./adapters/{{ package_name }}.py   # relative to nautilus.yaml
    class: {{ class_name }}
    source_type: {{ source_type }}
```

Note: local-path loading imports a single module file; copy
`src/{{ package_name }}/__init__.py` to a standalone `.py` file for this
mode (no relative imports).
